## Part two linear Regression 1) split data into train and test set.

library(caTools)
set.seed(101)

## split up the sample
sample <- sample.split(df$G3, SplitRatio = 0.7)
## 70% of data -> train
train <- subset(df, sample == TRUE)
## 30% will be test
test <- subset(df,sample == FALSE)

Building the model:

remember: model <- lm(y~. , data)## uses all features in the model

## train and build:
model <- lm(G3 ~ ., data = train)

## run model

## interpret the model.
print(summary(model))

Residuals tell you the difference between the predicted values and the actual values of the the data. The little stars tells you if the coefficients are valuable for our model.

Ploting residuals of model.

res <- residuals(model)
head(res)
##          1          2          3          6          9         11 
##  1.4684389  1.8826707  1.1866990 -2.2440152  0.5974865  0.8583062
res <- as.data.frame(res)
ggplot(res, aes(res)) + geom_histogram(fill = "blue", alpha = .5)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

plot(model)

Predictions

G3.predictions <- predict(model, test)
results <- cbind(G3.predictions, test$G3)
colnames(results) <- c('predicted', 'actual')

results <- as.data.frame(results)
print(head(results))
##    predicted actual
## 4  12.682507     15
## 5   9.433677     10
## 7  11.312310     11
## 8   3.101530      6
## 10 15.564674     15
## 13 14.190360     14

fixing negative predictions

to_zero <- function(x){
        if (x < 0){
                return(0)
        } else{
                return(x)
        }
}
## take care of negative values
results$predicted <- sapply(results$predicted, to_zero)

evaluating our model

mse <- mean((results$actual - results$predicted)^2)
print("MSE")
## [1] "MSE"
print(mse)
## [1] 3.991675
## RMSE
print("RMSE")
## [1] "RMSE"
print(mse^0.5)
## [1] 1.997918
SSE <- sum((results$predicted - results$actual)^2)
SST <- sum((mean(df$G3) - results$actual)^2)

R2 <- 1 - SSE/SST
print('R2')
## [1] "R2"
print(R2)
## [1] 0.8044477

R^2 of .80 means that our model accounts for 80% of the data.
